				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$f_{uh}$\end{document}. See text for more discussion

Panels d–f in Fig. 16 show rapid variations in the frequency of the upper hybrid band, hence the electron density. For these orbits, the interpretation of the spectrum is reasonably straightforward, but it is necessary to track the rapid excursions in frequency. Finally, panels g–i show deep erosions of the plasmasphere and very low densities beyond the plasmapause. These are indicative of an active magnetosphere and present the greatest challenge in the interpretation of the spectrum for the purposes of inferring the plasma density. As can be seen, there are multiple harmonics in the spectrum. These consist of multiple electron cyclotron harmonics between fce\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
